<div id="review_2220169984" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2220169984" />
    <a title="Kevin Lopez (on sabbatical)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22976975-kevin-lopez-on-sabbatical"><img alt="Kevin Lopez (on sabbatical)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1376112680p2/22976975.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2220169984?book_show_action=true">Jan 10, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kevin Lopez (on sabbatical)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kevin Lopez (on sabbatical)" href="/user/show/22976975-kevin-lopez-on-sabbatical">Kevin Lopez (on sabbatical)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2220169984" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16357807302451687287">Thoroughly underwhelming<br/><br/>Despite the role Lawrence Krauss played in the discovery (or invocation, as some prefer) of dark energy in the 1990s - which was significant - here I found his writing weak; littered with facile analogies and uninspired, uninspiring analysis and commentary. I heard him speak once and he was quite good (although recently I listened to him on a new podcast he started and he was pretty awful, despite having as his guest the brilliant astrophysicist and Astronomer Royal Marti</span>
  <span id="freeText16357807302451687287" style="display:none">Thoroughly underwhelming<br /><br />Despite the role Lawrence Krauss played in the discovery (or invocation, as some prefer) of dark energy in the 1990s - which was significant - here I found his writing weak; littered with facile analogies and uninspired, uninspiring analysis and commentary. I heard him speak once and he was quite good (although recently I listened to him on a new podcast he started and he was pretty awful, despite having as his guest the brilliant astrophysicist and Astronomer Royal Martin Rees), but in <i>A Universe From Nothing</i> he somehow manages to take what are extraordinarily interesting, exciting, and cutting-edge concepts and render them almost mundane. <br />If this had been a longer book I might not have finished it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16357807302451687287" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

